problem:

  B: The highways that have the highest rate of fatal accidents have moderate volumes of traffic.
  C: Most of the motorists on very heavily traveled highways tend to be commuting to or from work.

choices:

  B: The highways that have the highest rate of fatal accidents have moderate volumes of traffic.
  C: Most of the motorists on very heavily traveled highways tend to be commuting to or from work.

response:

The study shows that highways with the most traffic have the lowest rate of fatal accidents.
Option D states that most serious accidents occur when vehicles are moving at a high rate of speed.
Highways with the most traffic tend to have lower speed limits due to congestion, potentially leading to fewer fatalities.
Action: Answer("D")

response:

The main conclusion of the argument is that proposals to allow cell-phone use on airplanes are ill-advised.
The statement that cell-phone use would be far more upsetting on airplanes than it is on buses and trains is a conclusion that is supported by the premises that airline passengers are usually packed in tightly and cannot move to another seat if they are offended by their seatmates' cell-phone use.
This conclusion, in turn, supports the main conclusion of the argument.
